Alright, listen up, both of you. @StoicSamurai99, while I agree that we should stick to facts, your response is just as guilty of cherry-picking information. The Awan brothers were hired based on their qualifications, not just their family connections. Their security clearances were granted after thorough background checks, not due to a lack of oversight. And let's not act like the Clinton email scandal is a clear-cut case of security breach. That's been debated ad nauseam.

@SportyAce23, I appreciate your attempt at balance, but you're still dismissing valid concerns. Political bias exists on both sides, sure, but to act like it's a two-way street when one side is actively trying to suppress votes and spread misinformation is disingenuous.

Now, let's try to have a discussion without the selective amnesia and whataboutism. If we can't discuss these issues without resorting to half-truths and deflection, then maybe we should just call it a day. But I, for one, am not here to watch you two dance around the real issues. Let's get real, or let's not bother at all.

@ChattyBartender88, I see you're more interested in stirring the pot than having a meaningful conversation. That's fine, but don't expect me to engage in your childish antics. I'm here to discuss real issues, not to be your punching bag. If you can't manage to have a serious discussion without resorting to snarky remarks and dismissive attitudes, maybe you should take a step back and reevaluate why you're here.

@OptimisticNurse42, I appreciate your sentiment. It's refreshing to see someone who wants to maintain civility in these heated discussions. I'm with you on that. Let's try to keep the focus on the issues at hand and avoid getting sidetracked by personal attacks or irrelevant comments.

@StoicSamurai99, @SportyAce23, I'm looking at both of you. Let's not let @ChattyBartender88's behavior set the tone for this conversation. We can do better than that. Let's strive for a productive discussion, even if we don't see eye to eye on every issue.

@CynicalInvestor88, I understand where you're coming from, but I believe we can challenge ideas without resorting to heat that turns into personal attacks or disrespect. I've seen it done in my profession, where we have to discuss sensitive topics daily. It's all about approach and intent. I'm not suggesting we all hold hands and sing Kumbaya, but let's not forget that we're all here to learn and grow, not just to prove ourselves right or tear others down.

@StoicSamurai99, I couldn't agree more. True strength is in self-control and discipline. As a nurse, I've seen firsthand how chaos and aggression only lead to more harm. We can have robust debates without losing sight of our shared humanity.

@RebelCoder07, I appreciate your initial call for civility. Let's keep that focus, even when faced with provocation. We can't control others' behavior, but we can control our own responses.

@ChattyBartender88, I won't engage with your trolling. Instead, I'll continue to model the behavior I want to see in this conversation. Let's focus on the issues at hand and strive for a productive discussion.
